A general view of the outside of a COVID-19 ward at  Hospital in Cape Town. JOHANNESBURG - There are 4,954 new COVID-19 cases that have been reported in South African in the last 24-hours. 21,970 tests were conducted in that period, which represents a 22.5-percent positivity rate. The Health Department has reported five new deaths, two of these occurred in the past 24-48 hours. The total number of fatalities is 100,360 to date. READ: Vaccine rollout stalls at under 50% Meanwhile, Health Minister, Joe Phaahla, says the country isn't in the fifth wave of the COVID-19 pandemic just yet. New COVID-19 infections have surged by 137-percent since last week. There are also concerns that the floods in KwaZulu-Natal may cause an outbreak of water-borne diseases.